<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-001-134  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 001 134.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  Jan 1 1990 v12 n1 p30(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>I swear... (licensing programmers)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mace, Scott.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Software quality has become a major industry and regulatory issueas a result of highly publicized failures.andP;  Damage caused by asmall error in software can grow exponentially when data is usedby large numbers of workers and by other programs.andP;  Many statesare working to strengthen computer crime statutes, and some haveproposed licensing of programmers as a method of combatingviruses.andP;  Proponents of such oversight rules say that programmingis a form of engineering and should be covered by rules similar tobuilding codes; opponents counter that programmers are artists andcannot be held to objective standards.andP;  The major impediment toimposing quality standards is the fact that bugs usually cannot betraced to any single programmer.andP;  Bugs occur when publishers tryto combine the works of many people into a single package.andP;  It isalso difficult to prove that viruses result from malice.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ProgrammersComputer IndustryFuture of ComputingTrendsSoftware Quality.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>